893 

894 

895 # Exit processing: process_*_exits 

896 # 

897 # These functions process the four kinds of jump exits: break, continue, 

898 # raise, and return. To figure out where an exit goes, we have to look at 

899 # the block stack context. For example, a break will jump to the nearest 

900 # enclosing loop block, or the nearest enclosing finally block, whichever 

901 # is nearer.

931 # Handlers: _handle__* 

932 # 

933 # Each handler deals with a specific AST node type, dispatched from 

934 # add_arcs. Handlers return the set of exits from that node, and can 

935 # also call self.add_arc to record arcs they find. These functions mirror 

936 # the Python semantics of each syntactic construct. See the docstring 

937 # for add_arcs to understand the concept of exits from a node. 

938 # 

939 # Every node type that represents a statement should have a handler, or it 

940 # should be listed in OK_TO_DEFAULT.

1297if AST_DUMP: # pragma: debugging 3.10.macos-latest.c3.10.macos-latest.py3.10.ubuntu-latest.c3.10.ubuntu-latest.py3.10.windows-latest.c3.10.windows-latest.py3.6.macos-latest.c3.6.macos-latest.py3.6.ubuntu-latest.c3.6.ubuntu-latest.py3.6.windows-latest.c3.6.windows-latest.py3.7.macos-latest.c3.7.macos-latest.py3.7.ubuntu-latest.c3.7.ubuntu-latest.py3.7.windows-latest.c3.7.windows-latest.py3.8.macos-latest.c3.8.macos-latest.py3.8.ubuntu-latest.c3.8.ubuntu-latest.py3.8.windows-latest.c3.8.windows-latest.py3.9.macos-latest.c3.9.macos-latest.py3.9.ubuntu-latest.c3.9.ubuntu-latest.py3.9.windows-latest.c3.9.windows-latest.pypypy3.macos-latest.pypypy3.ubuntu-latest.py

1298 # Code only used when dumping the AST for debugging. 

1299 

1300 SKIP_DUMP_FIELDS = ["ctx"] 

1301 

1302 def _is_simple_value(value): 

1303 """Is `value` simple enough to be displayed on a single line?""" 

1304 return ( 

1305 value in [None, [], (), {}, set()] or 

1306 isinstance(value, (str, int, float)) 

1307 ) 

1308 

1309 def ast_dump(node, depth=0): 

1310 """Dump the AST for `node`. 

1311 

1312 This recursively walks the AST, printing a readable version. 

1313 

1314 """ 

1315 indent = " " * depth 

1316 if not isinstance(node, ast.AST): 

1317 print(f"{indent}<{node.__class__.__name__} {node!r}>") 

1318 return 

1319 

1320 lineno = getattr(node, "lineno", None) 

1321 if lineno is not None: 

1322 linemark = f" @ {node.lineno},{node.col_offset}" 

1323 if hasattr(node, "end_lineno"): 

1324 linemark += ":" 

1325 if node.end_lineno != node.lineno: 

1326 linemark += f"{node.end_lineno}," 

1327 linemark += f"{node.end_col_offset}" 

1328 else: 

1329 linemark = "" 

1330 head = f"{indent}<{node.__class__.__name__}{linemark}" 

1331 

1332 named_fields = [ 

1333 (name, value) 

1334 for name, value in ast.iter_fields(node) 

1335 if name not in SKIP_DUMP_FIELDS 

1336 ] 

1337 if not named_fields: 

1338 print(f"{head}>") 

1339 elif len(named_fields) == 1 and _is_simple_value(named_fields[0][1]): 

1340 field_name, value = named_fields[0] 

1341 print(f"{head} {field_name}: {value!r}>") 

1342 else: 

1343 print(head) 

1344 if 0: 

1345 print("{}# mro: {}".format( 

1346 indent, ", ".join(c.__name__ for c in node.__class__.__mro__[1:]), 

1347 )) 

1348 next_indent = indent + " " 

1349 for field_name, value in named_fields: 

1350 prefix = f"{next_indent}{field_name}:" 

1351 if _is_simple_value(value): 

1352 print(f"{prefix} {value!r}") 

1353 elif isinstance(value, list): 

1354 print(f"{prefix} [") 

1355 for n in value: 

1356 ast_dump(n, depth + 8) 

1357 print(f"{next_indent}]") 

1358 else: 

1359 print(prefix) 

1360 ast_dump(value, depth + 8) 

1361 

1362 print(f"{indent}>")
